<DOC><DOCNO> AP890707-0002 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 2343EST</FILEID><FIRST>u w AM-Nixon-China 240   07-07 0225</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Nixon-China, 240</SECOND><HEAD>Nixon Planning China Trip: Report</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Former President Richard Nixon, who reopenedties with China in the 1970s, is planning to visit China inSeptember, according to a published report.   U.S. officials and diplomatic sources were quoted in Saturday'seditions of The Washington Post as saying that Nixon and formerSecretary of State Henry Kissinger were likely to be among the firstprominent Americans to visit China since the bloody crackdown onpro-democracy demonstrators last month.   Nixon did not respond to inquiries about his China plans, thenewspaper said.   Kissinger, who served under Nixon and helped forge relations withChina, was quoted as saying he was considering a ``long-standinginvitation'' to visit China in October to take part in agovernment-sponsored investment conference.   ``I won't conduct foreign policy on my own,'' Kissinger said. ``Iwouldn't do anything without consulting the administration.''   President Bush has barred high-level official trips to China as asign of U.S. displeasure with the massacre in Tiananmen Square. Theorder extends only to executive branch officials.   Nixon's trip to China in February 1972 re-establishedSino-American relations for the first time since the 1949 communistrevolution. He has made three other trips to China.   Nixon has expressed disapproval of U.S. sanctions, saying thatmessages should be sent through private channels asking the Chineseto show restraint.</TEXT></DOC>